I don't get the skill to wear it until level 15 however, which I may or may not make before beta ends. <br>
<br>
The armsman is the tank of tanks, as I have a good AC, the ability to wear most any armor and a good selection of weapons. As a fighter, I started with slash, crush or thrust, and chose to specialize in Slash, putting nothing into crush or thrust. This effects the combat styles I can get, as I've gotten no crushing or thrusting styles, only slashing. But were I to choose it, I could make a warrior based off any of them, or try to balance them all out. At earlier levels, though, you only get specialization points on a 1/level basis, so diversifying at lower levels could hurt, in that you'll be a jack of all trades, but won't be especially good at any of them. At 6th, I began to get 2/level in spec points, which is good. At level 5, when I chose the Armsman profession, I gained Shield and Polearm specs at 1, and I've trained them both up to 4. The shield skills give me the ability to stun the mob, with the Style Numb, and the Guard Style, which so long as I'm in melee range of the party member I'm trying to guard, I can try to deflect damage from them with my shield. Only used it once so far, and the cleric ran away from me, so it didn't work very well. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Each of the styles has an endurance cost (which fighters use much like mana). A fighter with low endurance is much less effective than he is with endurance, as the styles add bonus damage to your normal hits, as well as do special things like taunt (with the Enrage style - spec 8 in Slash), bleed (DOT like damage) and stun (with the Numb style). As an armsman, choose the weapons you want to spec in EARLY, or you will suck at them. Focus is more important in DAoC than in EQ... you have to focus on a skill or you will not be nearly as effective. At 10th level, I'll gain 2handed slash abilities, which I'll probably use. <br>
<br>
For tradeskills, I think Armorcrafting is the main skill and weaponcrafting a secondary one. Armorcrafting is a &quot;break even skill&quot; ... i.e. at the beginning levels, you can break even or lose just a bit of money while building it up. Weaponcrafting is lose money trade skill. It is EXTREMELY expensive. Train up your armor crafting first, then when you can make money or sustain yourself with armor, try to learn your weapons. Also remember that you can wear leather armour, which is controlled by tailoring, so get your tailoring high as well, because for things like plate and chain, you'll be required to make the same piece (gaunts, helm, etc.) in leather armour before you can make the plate piece. <br>
<br>
One good tactic for an armsman is learn to use the 3rd person view when grouping. You need to be able to move when the adds get through to your healers, and if you don't see them, you don't know to attack them or to guard them. The 3rd person view also has the added benefit of getting to watch all those cool spell effects and fighting styles. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  When soloing, don't try yellows unless completely full on endurance and health. Even then, you'll die at least 25-50% of the time against yellows, especially if you have adds. Most blues won't kill you unless you were low on health, and you can take 2-3 greens before needing to rest up. Until you get to 15th level and get crossbows, you won't be able to do any ranged pulling, so get used to pulling by walking backwards. <br>
<br>
Haemish<br>
